{"source_key":"sha256-9b0f9c3f961abf38b897cbefe7e9ac46","record_index":70,"record_hash":"sha256:080054544a1fc284629ae868b7c21a1e97fb2dc7dad61a5ab9a62986737a1f95","timestamp":"2026-05-11T19:50:22.489Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 94bfe3\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1011\nOutput:\n     1\t# Requirements and Goals\n     2\t\n     3\t## Problem\n     4\t\n     5\tAI coding sessions contain useful provenance: prompts, assistant messages, tool\n     6\tcalls, plans, and generated context. Today that data lives in agent-specific\n     7\tlocal storage and is not connected to the Git repository in a portable way.\n     8\t\n     9\tGitMeta gives GitButler a Git-native place to store that context without\n    10\tpolluting the worktree. GitButler needs a small capture layer that reads selected\n    11\tagent transcripts, normalizes them enough to store, and writes them through\n    12\tGitMeta.\n    13\t\n    14\t## POC Goals\n    15\t\n    16\tThe first milestone should prove the storage and command shape, not solve agent\n    17\tdiscovery or publishing.\n    18\t\n    19\t- Capture Codex and Claude JSONL transcripts from an explicit path.\n    20\t- Expose capture through a hidden, feature-gated CLI command.\n    21\t- Store redacted, shareable-ready `gitbutler:*` data in GitMeta.\n    22\t- Keep the data project-scoped by default so future branch/PR/commit references\n    23\t  can point to durable sessions.\n    24\t- Allow an explicit GitMeta target to reference the durable session key.\n    25\t- Make repeated capture idempotent.\n    26\t- Provide an explicit sync command that uses GitMeta's configured metadata\n    27\t  remote behavior.\n    28\t- Keep code changes focused in `crates/but-agentlog` plus the smallest CLI\n    29\t  bridge.\n    30\t\n    31\tThe detailed implementation contract lives in\n    32\t[First POC Implementation Contract](first-poc-implementation.md).\n    33\t\n    34\t## Product Direction\n    35\t\n    36\tThe POC should point toward two later use cases:\n    37\t\n    38\t- session handoff across machines and agents after GitMeta exchange and resume\n    39\t  UX are designed\n    40\t- colleague/reviewer browsing through a future GitButler web view that can show\n    41\t  the prompts, responses, tool activity, and prompting qu\n[TRUNCATED]\nhose use cases require project-scoped sessions plus relationship keys. They do\n    45\tnot require branch inference in the POC.\n    46\t\n    47\t## Later Goals\n    48\t\n    49\t- Capture the current or recent AI coding session without an explicit path.\n    50\t- Prefer deterministic hook-style capture when an agent can provide an exact\n    51\t  transcript path or session id.\n    52\t- Search known agent locations, filtered by repository, when no exact input is\n    53\t  available.\n    54\t- Add Cursor only after Codex and Claude establish the shared shape. Cursor needs\n    55\t  a separate design pass because its normal chat history is local SQLite and its\n    56\t  official portable format is Markdown export.\n    57\t- Decide later whether sync should run automatically as part of broader\n    58\t  GitButler push/fetch flows.\n    59\t\n    60\tAgent-specific discovery notes live in [Capture Workflow](capture-workflow.md).\n    61\t\n    62\t## Non-Goals\n    63\t\n    64\t- No automatic background capture in the first milestone.\n    65\t- No heuristic session discovery in the first milestone.\n    66\t- No automatic GitMeta serialization, push, fetch, or sync in the first\n    67\t  milestone.\n    68\t- No branch, commit, change-id, or pull request inference in the first milestone.\n    69\t- No machine-wide scraping of AI tool storage.\n    70\t- No dependency on provider-specific crates such as `but-claude`.\n    71\t- No `meta:local:*` storage for the main session records; these records are meant\n    72\t  to support future handoff and sharing.\n    73\t- No transcript copies on branch, commit, change, or pull request targets.\n    74\t  Non-project targets should reference durable project session keys.\n    75\t\n    76\t## Open Questions\n    77\t\n    78\t- What user-facing privacy controls should exist before shareable-ready\n    79\t  transcript contents are serialized or pushed?\n    80\t- Which explicit target associations should future hooks add automatically, and\n    81\t  when?\n    82\t- What redaction policy is good enough before remote exchange?\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T19:50:22.489Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}